11/04/2003
BELGRADE, Serbia-Montenegro -- In an interview with <I>Blic</I> daily Thursday (10 April), former Yugoslav President Vojislav Kostunica said he would not ask war crimes indictees Ratko Mladic and retired Yugoslav Army Gen Veselin Sljivancanin to surrender. Kostunica said he never promised to seek their surrender during his mandate.
Kostunia again denied that some of his aides were involved in the planning of the late Serbian Prime Minister Zoran Djindjic's assassination. Kostunica accused the Serbian government of carrying out a "witch hunt" and trying to eliminate its political rivals.
In other news, Serbian Deputy Prime Minister Nebojsa Covic resigned from the position of Belgrade's co-ordinator on Kosovo. He said he now finds the job unrewarding due to "partisan petty interests, manipulations and unfounded attacks". He will stay on until a replacement is found. (Blic, B92, Tanjug, BBC, FoNet, AP, AFP - 10/04/03)
